<h2>Manufacturing Processes and Cross-Contamination Risks</h2>

<p>Even if a product's ingredients are gluten-free, cross-contamination during manufacturing can pose a risk for individuals with celiac disease or severe gluten sensitivity. Cross-contamination can occur when gluten-free products are processed on the same equipment as gluten-containing products, leading to trace amounts of gluten in the final product.</p>

<p>Fairlife takes precautions to minimize the risk of cross-contamination. The company follows strict manufacturing protocols and conducts regular testing to ensure that their products meet gluten-free standards. According to Fairlife, their Chocolate Protein Shake is produced in facilities that are free from gluten-containing ingredients, reducing the likelihood of cross-contamination.</p>

<h2>Certifications and Labeling</h2>

<p>One of the most reliable ways to determine if a product is gluten-free is to look for certifications from recognized organizations. Fairlife Chocolate Protein Shake is not certified gluten-free by organizations such as the Gluten-Free Certification Organization (GFCO) or the Celiac Support Association (CSA). However, the product is labeled as gluten-free on its packaging, which indicates that it contains less than 20 parts per million (ppm) of gluten, the threshold established by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for gluten-free labeling.</p>

<p>While the lack of third-party certification may be a concern for some, the FDA's gluten-free labeling standards provide a reasonable level of assurance for most consumers. For those with extreme sensitivity, it may be advisable to consult with a healthcare professional before incorporating the product into their diet.</p>

